<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>
<p>Know Your Zone: Understanding your USDA hardiness zone can help you choose plants that are best suited to your climate and will thrive in your garden.</p>


<p>Plan Your Layout: Before planting, sketch out a rough plan of your garden layout. Consider factors like sunlight exposure, plant height, and spacing requirements.
    Healthy plants start with healthy soil. Invest in good quality soil amendments like compost and organic matter to improve soil fertility and structure.
</p>

<p>Water Wisely: Avoid overwatering by watering deeply but infrequently. Early morning is the best time to water to minimize evaporation and give plants time to dry off before nightfall.</p>

<p>
    Mulch Matters: Mulching helps retain moisture, suppress weeds, and regulate soil temperature. Use organic mulches like bark chips or straw for best results.

    Continuous Learning: Gardening is a continual learning process. Stay curious, experiment with new plants and techniques, and don't be afraid to learn from both successes and failures.
</p>

<p>Companion Planting: Planting certain crops together can help repel pests, attract beneficial insects, and improve pollination. Research companion planting combinations for your specific crops.</p>

<p>Practice Crop Rotation: Rotate your crops each season to prevent soil depletion and minimize pest and disease buildup. Follow a simple rotation schedule of leafy greens, root vegetables, legumes, and fruiting plants.</p>

<p>Prune Regularly: Pruning helps maintain plant health, shape, and productivity. Remove dead or diseased branches, and prune back overgrown or crowded growth to improve air circulation and light penetration.</p>